1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Dundra Mifflin, this is Aaron.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
He's not available right now.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:09,000
Uh-huh.

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,000
Yes.

5
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Sure, I'll give him the message when he gets up.

6
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Gets back.

7
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Michael had chicken pot pie for lunch.

8
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Actually, let me rephrase that.

9
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Michael had an entire chicken pot pie for lunch.

10
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Let me be more specific.

11
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Michael ate an entire family-sized chicken pot pie for lunch,

12
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,000
and then he promptly fell asleep.

13
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:33,000
So we're all trying to be very quiet

14
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,000
so as to not wake him up before 5 p.m.,

15
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:38,000
which actually should be in about...

16
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:44,000
10 minutes.

17
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Okay, I'm gonna go in there and change the computer.

18
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Are you sure you can change his watch?

19
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,000
I can do it.

20
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:51,000
What do you need from me?

21
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Normally I don't condone leaving early,

22
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,000
but I have an appointment with the horse doctor.

23
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
How that horse became a doctor, I don't know.

24
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Ha ha ha ha!

25
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
No, I'm kidding.

26
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,000
He's just a regular doctor who shoots your horse in the head

27
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:06,000
when its leg is broken.

28
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Hmm.

29
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Hmm. Hmm.

30
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Hup, hup.

31
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Like clockwork.

32
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Oh!

33
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:23,000
Ha ha ha ha!

34
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Oh, no.

35
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Oh, no.

36
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Uh-oh.

37
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Oh, it's so funny.

38
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Glad to be there.

39
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,000
Oh, okay, geography joke.

40
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Ha ha ha ha!

41
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Oh, wow, okay.

42
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,000
All right, let's all go home.

43
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Come on. See you all tomorrow.

44
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:44,000
See you later, Michael.

45
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Michael!

46
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Yeah!

47
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Whoo!

48
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Ah!

49
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Yeah!

50
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:06,000
All right, you ready for this?

51
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Yeah, we walk around, everyone sees our faces,

52
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:08,000
and we leave, right?

53
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:09,000
Yeah.

54
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Okay.

55
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Wait, should I have left the car running?

56
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Oh.

57
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Oh, don't get us wrong, we like picnics.

58
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Come on, who doesn't like a picnic?

59
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Tell them what happened last year.

60
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,000
I had this huge spider in my baseball mat.

61
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
No, no, the guy you hit on me.

62
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Oh, right, some drunk guy hit on Pam last year.

63
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Said he was grabbing her for balance.

64
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Yeah, you don't grab these for balance.

65
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
No.

66
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,000
How you doing, Stanley?

67
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Same as I was yesterday, just now I'm outside.

68
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
This party sucks, Meredith.

69
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:42,000
What do you mean, mom?

70
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Look here, Meredith.

71
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:46,000
In the car, now!

72
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,000
All day!

73
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Again?

74
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Look, Jake, unbelievable.

75
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,000
You have to work hard to get to play hard.

76
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:56,000
And I think people work all year long

77
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
just so they can have that one beautiful day

78
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
outdoors, hanging out with their family.

79
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
I usually bring a guy from the condo complex.

80
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
But this year,

81
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,000
I would just rather catch up

82
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
with some of my old friends from the other branches.

83
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
Like Dan Gore.

84
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And Holly will be here.

85
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
We exchanged emails.

86
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
And that guy from Akron?

87
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
I'm gonna say 30.

88
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Ah, 40.

89
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Insect repellent, which we clearly need,

90
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
reduces the effectiveness of SPF.

91
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Good point, but I've thought of that already.

92
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Combination SPF, repellent.

93
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Whoa. How many?

94
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Of course. You think the EPA would ever allow that much DEET?

95
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Rolf is my best friend.

96
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
We met in a shoe store.

97
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
I heard him asking for a shoe that could increase his speed

98
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
and not leave any tracks.

99
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Michael, isn't that Holly?

100
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,000
We're just friends.

101
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
Hey, hey, wait a second.

102
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Who let you in here?

103
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Is what I want to know.

104
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Oh, no.

105
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
I see they're letting just anybody in here.

106
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Yeah, that's right.

107
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,000
All right.

108
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Mm-hmm.

109
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Hey.

110
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Hi.

111
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
You remember AJ, my boyfriend?

112
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
A little bit.

113
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
I meet a lot of people.

114
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Hey, Michael.

115
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
So would you guys like some lemonade?

116
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Or one of you?

117
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Or both of you?

118
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Either or.

119
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Combinations are endless.

120
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Lemonade sounds great.

121
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
I'd love an iced tea, actually.

122
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
You can go to hell.

123
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:42,000
I'm kidding.

124
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Sure, I will get you the best iced tea in the world.

125
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:48,000
I lied to Kevin.

126
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Holly and I can never be just friends.

127
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
I wrote down a list of bullet points

128
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:54,000
why Holly and I should be together,

129
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
and I'm going to find the perfect moment today

130
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
and I'm going to tell her.

131
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Number one, Holly.

132
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
You and I are soup snakes.

133
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
And the reason is

134
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,000
because in terms of the soup,

135
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
we like tea.

136
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
That doesn't make any sense.

137
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
We're soulmates.

138
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
Holly and I are soulmates.

139
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Jim.

140
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Pam.

141
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
Hey, how are you? Hey, Charles.

142
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:22,000
Hey, nice day. Yeah.

143
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
Must be nice to get a rest from all your rest.

144
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,000
I don't get it.

145
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:28,000
He's not even my boss anymore.

146
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:30,000
I'm sorry to beat him up for you.

147
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
I shouldn't have to ask you to do stuff like that.

148
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
You should just do it.

149
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
Listen up, everyone. I've gone over this line up very carefully.

150
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:38,000
We cannot forget the humiliation

151
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
we suffered last year at the softball game

152
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
with Jim's whole spider in the mitt incident.

153
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
Right?

154
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Well, I could have died, so...

155
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
I looked it up online afterwards.

156
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Aaron, back row.

157
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Ryan, you move up a row.

158
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Broomigo.

159
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
You think you could put Aaron on my row?

160
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
I mean, if...

161
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa. Wait a minute. I get it.

162
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
You want her to set you up

163
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
so you can spike it.

164
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
Uh...

165
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,000
I tell you what, I'm gonna do you one better.

166
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
I'm gonna put you next to Phyllis.

167
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
She's the best setter on the team.

168
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
That's... you sly dog.

169
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Not what I meant. Come on, folks!

170
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
What is up with you two, Holly?

171
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Uh, not much.

172
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:22,000
We're designing a house.

173
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
Cool. For who?

174
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,000
For us.

175
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
Wow!

176
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,000
I'm designing a chair.

177
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
It's part of your pants.

178
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,000
Sit down. You're supported.

179
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
I remember your chair pants idea.

180
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Yeah.

181
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
I like that. Put me down for a pair.

182
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
I'm a size 34 waist.

183
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
All right, fatty. I will do it.

184
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
You know what? We should actually rehearse.

185
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Okay.

186
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
You guys are really gonna do this?

187
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
You bet your fat ass we are.

188
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Well, in his infinite wisdom,

189
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
David Wallace has authorized us

190
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
to put on a little presentation

191
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
about the history of Dunder Mifflin.

192
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,000
Yep. The whole comedy team

193
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,000
is back together again.

194
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
That's right.

195
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
Have you heard the news?

196
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
Extra, extra, read all about it.

197
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Newspapers for sale!

198
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Sit down.

199
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
Are you blind?

200
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Are you blind?

201
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,000
Are you blind?

202
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:26,000
Sir,

203
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
with the glasses, are you literally blind?

204
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
I'm concerned you might be in danger.

205
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,000
These are expensive Ray-Bans, jackass.

206
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
Okay. I was just looking out for you.

207
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,000
You're doing great, by the way.

208
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
Thanks.

209
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:40,000
I got it.

210
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
Oh!

211
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Oh, Kevin, come on!

212
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Are you blind? I could have gotten that, idiot!

213
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Can you see things with your eyeballs?

214
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Come on, people! We need to get our heads

215
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
in the game with focus.

216
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Come on, you're better than this!

217
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,000
I am better than this!

218
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,000
Phyllis, why are you sitting on the ground?

219
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:00,000
We've been out here for a while.

220
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,000
I don't need this.

221
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
God!

222
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
Applause
